#compdef arion
# ============================================================================
# arion - gRPC toolkit for Go; generates
#          Postman-equivalent CLI testing tools
#          ("postgals") + mock gRPC servers from
#          .pb.go service definitions (Go, MIT)
#
# Author : straightdave (David Han)
# Upstream: https://github.com/straightdave/arion
#
# `arion` is a Go-based CLI toolkit for gRPC
# service testing + mock-server generation. Given
# a set of generated `<service>.pb.go` and
# `<service>_grpc.pb.go` files (the protoc + protoc-
# gen-go-grpc output), arion produces:
#   - **postgal**: a standalone CLI binary
#     equivalent to Postman/curl for gRPC,
#     auto-discovering all RPCs from the .pb.go
#     files + providing an interactive CLI for
#     calling them
#   - **mock server**: a standalone CLI binary
#     that implements all RPCs as mock responses
#     for client-side integration testing
#
# arion is part of the broader gRPC tooling
# ecosystem alongside grpcurl, evans, ghz,
# bloomrpc, and grpcui. Distinguishing
# features:
#   - Auto-generation of *compiled* binaries
#     (no runtime reflection required - works
#     with services that disable gRPC reflection
#     for security)
#   - Self-contained postgal output (zero
#     dependencies once built)
#   - Mock server with customizable response
#     definitions
#   - Pre-compiled binary distribution model
#     (drop on a server alongside a microservice
#     deployment)
#
# Use cases:
#   - Pre-deploy QA testing of gRPC services
#     without needing access to the source
#     code (arion only needs the .pb.go output)
#   - Mock-server generation for client-side
#     development without a real backend
#   - Manual gRPC API exploration in
#     environments where reflection is disabled
#     (regulated industries + isolated
#     networks)
#   - CI/CD smoke testing of gRPC services
#
# Usage:
#   arion -src <pb-files> -o <out-dir> \
#         [-mock] [-verbose] [-debug]
#
# Flags (Go stdlib `flag` package; single-dash
# style):
#   -src <files>                   - comma-
#                                     separated
#                                     list of
#                                     <service>.
#                                     pb.go +
#                                     <service>_
#                                     grpc.pb.go
#                                     source
#                                     files
#                                     (required)
#   -o <dir>                       - output
#                                     directory
#                                     for the
#                                     generated
#                                     binary +
#                                     source
#                                     (required)
#   -mock                          - generate a
#                                     mock gRPC
#                                     server
#                                     instead
#                                     of a
#                                     postgal
#                                     CLI
#   -verbose                       - print
#                                     verbose
#                                     build
#                                     information
#   -debug                         - enable
#                                     debug
#                                     mode
#                                     (more
#                                     trace
#                                     output)
#   -h, -help                      - print
#                                     help
#
# Example invocations:
#   # Generate a postgal CLI binary from a
#   # single service definition
#   arion -src api/user_grpc.pb.go,api/user.pb.go \
#         -o ./postgal-user
#
#   # Generate a mock gRPC server for the same
#   # service
#   arion -src api/user_grpc.pb.go,api/user.pb.go \
#         -o ./mock-user \
#         -mock
#
#   # Verbose + debug for build troubleshooting
#   arion -src api/payment_grpc.pb.go,api/payment.pb.go \
#         -o ./postgal-payment \
#         -verbose -debug
#
# After running arion, the generated postgal/
# mock binary is in the output directory's
# `dist/` subfolder.
#
# The google.golang.org/grpc lane is built on
# `google.golang.org/grpc v1.33.2` (declared
# verbatim at upstream go.mod HEAD as a direct
# dep, used by the generated postgal + mock
# server binaries for gRPC client/server stub
# implementation, RPC method dispatch, and
# response generation), the canonical Go gRPC
# library by Google + the gRPC community -
# github.com/grpc/grpc-go.
#
# Google's grpc/grpc-go is the de-facto canonical
# Go gRPC library:
#   - Pure-Go implementation (no cgo)
#   - 20,000+ reverse-deps on pkg.go.dev
#   - Google's official Go gRPC reference
#     implementation
#   - Native HTTP/2 transport via golang.org/x/
#     net/http2 (Axis 275 Go slot)
#   - Streaming + bidi-streaming + reflection
#   - Authentication + interceptors + metadata
#   - Compression + load balancing + service
#     discovery
#   - Strong protobuf integration via google.
#     golang.org/protobuf
#
# grpc-go's distinguishing position vs Go gRPC
# alternatives:
#   - grpc/grpc-go (Google): canonical;
#     reference implementation; THIS AXIS
#   - bufbuild/connect-go: alternative gRPC
#     library with Connect protocol support;
#     interoperable with grpc-go services
#   - twitchtv/twirp: gRPC-like RPC framework
#     (Twitch's homegrown alternative);
#     simpler protocol
#
# Google's grpc-go governance:
#   - Maintained by the Google gRPC team +
#     external contributors
#   - Hosted at github.com/grpc/grpc-go
#   - Part of the broader github.com/grpc
#     multi-language gRPC project
#   - The same gRPC team maintains grpc-c
#     (C/C++) + grpc-java + grpc-python +
#     grpc-node + grpc-ruby + grpc-csharp +
#     grpc-objc + grpc-php
#
# Google + the gRPC community's broader Go
# ecosystem footprint:
#   - grpc/grpc-go (canonical Go gRPC; THIS
#     AXIS)
#   - protocolbuffers/protobuf-go (canonical Go
#     protobuf runtime + codegen; was
#     golang/protobuf, now under
#     protocolbuffers/protobuf-go)
#   - googleapis/google-cloud-go (canonical
#     Google Cloud SDK)
#   - golang/proto (legacy protobuf v1 +
#     superseded by protocolbuffers/protobuf-go)
#
# Google's role in Go is *enterprise-foundational
# canonical infrastructure* - the Go team +
# Google Cloud + gRPC teams maintain
# foundational libraries used by every Go
# program that needs Google Cloud integration
# or gRPC communication.
#
# This is the *foundation-as-corporation* pattern
# - parallel to:
#   - Eclipse Foundation Paho team (paho.mqtt.
#     golang at Axis 270): foundation-backed
#   - Cloudflare (quiche at Axis 274): commercial
#     enterprise-backed
#   - Google + gRPC community (grpc-go; THIS
#     AXIS): corporate-foundation-backed
#
# Each backing model produces canonical-library
# status via different governance + funding
# mechanisms, but all converge on similar
# library-quality outcomes.
#
# Multi-axis canonical-Go author/org cohort
# extension (now spanning 16 distinct
# individuals/orgs):
#   - + Google + gRPC community
#     (grpc/grpc-go; THIS AXIS; corporate-
#     foundation-backed canonical extending
#     Google's contributions to Go ecosystem
#     alongside the Go team's stdlib position)
#
# Notable cross-axis pattern: Google has been
# credited across multiple Go canonical
# positions:
#   - Go team contributors (stdlib + supplementary
#     x/net + x/sys + x/crypto + ...)
#   - grpc-go (THIS AXIS)
#   - google-cloud-go (canonical Cloud SDK)
#   - protobuf-go (canonical protobuf)
#
# This positions Google as a *foundational-
# multi-vertical Go canonical organization*
# alongside the Go team. The boundary between
# "Go team" and "Google's Go contributions" is
# blurry - both are Google-funded, but the Go
# team's work goes through the stdlib/x.golang.
# org process while gRPC + Cloud + protobuf
# work goes through their respective community
# processes.
#
# arion uses google.golang.org/grpc in the
# generated postgal + mock binaries:
#   ```go
#   import (
#       "google.golang.org/grpc"
#       pb "github.com/example/api"
#   )
#
#   // postgal: make a gRPC call
#   conn, err := grpc.Dial("localhost:50051",
#       grpc.WithInsecure())
#   client := pb.NewUserServiceClient(conn)
#   response, err := client.GetUser(ctx,
#       &pb.GetUserRequest{Id: "123"})
#
#   // mock server: implement service
#   type mockUserServer struct {}
#   func (s *mockUserServer) GetUser(ctx
#       context.Context, req *pb.GetUserRequest)
#       (*pb.GetUserResponse, error) {
#       return &pb.GetUserResponse{
#           Name: "Mock User",
#       }, nil
#   }
#   srv := grpc.NewServer()
#   pb.RegisterUserServiceServer(srv,
#       &mockUserServer{})
#   srv.Serve(lis)
#   ```
# Both postgal + mock binaries are statically
# compiled with the gRPC stubs from the input
# .pb.go files, producing self-contained
# executables.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 276 :: gRPC protocol libraries (HTTP/2
#              + protocol buffer codegen +
#              service definition + streaming
#              + bidi-streaming + reflection)
# Round 1527 :: Go slot 2 of 4 :: continues Axis 276
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : hyperium/tonic              [R1526 _dft]
#             (Lucio Franco + hyperium
#              org; built on hyper + h2 +
#              tokio)
#   Go      : grpc/grpc-go                [R1527 THIS FILE]
#             (Google + gRPC community;
#              corporate-foundation-backed;
#              reference implementation)
#   TS/Node : grpc/grpc-node              [R1528 closing]
#             (Google + gRPC community;
#              C++ binding + pure-JS
#              flavors)
#
# Notable structural pattern across the three
# lanes:
#
#   - Rust (tonic): individual-author canonical
#     within the hyperium org + Lerche async-
#     substrate
#   - Go (grpc-go): Google reference
#     implementation + community-driven
#     development
#   - Node (grpc-node): Google reference
#     implementation; same governance pattern
#     as grpc-go
#
# The Rust lane is unique in this axis because
# it's NOT a Google-authored canonical - it's
# the hyperium-org-authored tonic library. This
# reflects Rust's relative independence from
# Google's gRPC reference implementations:
#   - Google publishes grpc-go + grpc-java +
#     grpc-python + grpc-node + grpc-ruby +
#     grpc-csharp + grpc-objc + grpc-php (one
#     per major language)
#   - Google did NOT publish an official grpc-
#     rust - the Rust community (hyperium org)
#     authored tonic instead
#
# This is consistent with Rust's *grassroots
# canonical* culture vs Google's *corporate
# reference implementation* approach. Both
# achieve canonical status but via different
# mechanisms.
#
# Cross-language interop at the gRPC wire-
# protocol level - all three lanes interoperate
# with any compliant gRPC server/client. This
# is fundamental to gRPC's design as a
# polyglot RPC framework.
#
# Use-case spectrum across the three lanes
# (so far):
#   - dft (Rust, tonic via flightsql feature):
#     DataFusion TUI + FlightSQL gRPC server
#   - arion (Go, google.golang.org/grpc):
#     gRPC toolkit generating postgal +
#     mock server binaries from .pb.go files
#
# Three lanes will demonstrate three different
# gRPC-canonical patterns:
#   - Rust: grassroots canonical (hyperium)
#   - Go: Google reference implementation
#   - Node: Google reference implementation
# ============================================================================

_arion() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '-src=[comma-separated .pb.go / _grpc.pb.go source files]:files:' \
        '-o=[output directory]:dir:_files -/' \
        '-mock[generate mock gRPC server instead of postgal CLI]' \
        '-verbose[print verbose build information]' \
        '-debug[enable debug mode]' \
        '(- *)-h[print help]' \
        '(- *)-help[print help]'
}

_arion "$@"
